25|$|Renewed {{fighting}} {{broke out}} in April 2014 when the Burmese army attacked various KIA positions around Mansi Township, Kachin State and northern <b>Shan</b> <b>State</b> to eradicate timber smuggling and to control strategic routes around their strongholds. The Kachin Independence Army requested a meeting in Myitkyina on 10 May to lessen tensions between the sides.|$|E
25|$|One {{the largest}} Shan insurgent groups in Myanmar is the <b>Shan</b> <b>State</b> Army - South (SSA-S), which has around 6,000 to 8,000 soldiers, and {{was led by}} Yawd Serk until his {{resignation}} on 2 February 2014. The SSA-S maintains bases along the Myanmar-Thailand border, and signed a ceasefire agreement with the government on 2 December 2011.|$|E
25|$|Burma's junta {{signed an}} {{agreement}} with China Power Investment Corporation in May 2007 for the construction of seven hydroelectric dams along the Irrawaddy, Mali, and N'Mai River in Kachin State. The total planned output of all seven plants will be 15,160 MWs of electricity, making it the largest hydropower project in Burma, surpassing the 7,100 MW Tasang Dam in <b>Shan</b> <b>State.</b>|$|E
